40|$|The lowest mass {{object that}} Mother Nature makes {{through the process}} of “star formation” is {{currently}} unknown. While numerous very low mass <b>stars,</b> brown dwarfs, <b>and</b> <b>planets</b> have been found, their relation to each other remains unclear. Here I describe how the study of brown dwarfs has the potential to help us understand both <b>star</b> <b>and</b> <b>planet</b> formation mechanisms. I describe the physical traits attributed to <b>stars,</b> brown dwarfs, <b>and</b> planets; compare the mass functions of brown dwarfs and planets; and discuss how studies of brown dwarfs in both young clusters and in the field can be used to challenge <b>and</b> constrain <b>star</b> <b>and</b> <b>planet</b> formation theories...|$|R
