50|$|In {{this book}} Krauss {{discusses}} creating parts of an oxygen atom, the primary atoms of the Big Bang. Then he follows {{it through the}} remaining history of the Universe. As time has been passing by, the atom {{was a part of}} a supernova <b>and</b> <b>star</b> dust, <b>star</b> <b>and</b> <b>planet</b> systems, <b>and,</b> ultimately, a part of living cells.|$|R
40|$|The {{foundation}} {{for many of}} the missions recommended by the decadal survey is advances in infrared and submm detectors and receivers. We illustrate how NGST, SAFIR, and far infrared interferometry can use such devices to address fundamental questions in cosmology <b>and</b> <b>star</b> <b>and</b> <b>planet</b> formation, <b>and</b> furthermore how they enable a large discovery space. 1...|$|R
